<%# Transparency & methodology behind the energy estimates %>
<section class="w-full max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-4">
  <details class="group rounded-2xl bg-white dark:bg-neutral-800 shadow-sm border n-main-border">
    <summary class="flex cursor-pointer items-center gap-3 p-4 list-none n-main-hover rounded-2xl">
      <%= inline_svg "svg/question-circle.svg", title: "Methodology", alt: "Methodology", class: "w-5 h-5 text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400 shrink-0" %>
      <span class="text-sm font-semibold text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">How is the energy impact of models calculated?</span>
      <%= inline_svg "svg/chevron-down.svg", title: "Expand", alt: "Expand", class: "w-4 h-4 ml-auto text-neutral-400 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180 shrink-0" %>
    </summary>

    <div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-1 space-y-3 text-sm text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400 leading-relaxed border-t n-main-border">
      <p>
        Nosia uses the methodology developed by
        <a href="https://ecologits.ai" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 underline hover:text-blue-800 dark:hover:text-blue-300">Ecologits</a>
        (GenAI Impact) — the same one powering
        <a href="https://comparia.beta.gouv.fr" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 underline hover:text-blue-800 dark:hover:text-blue-300">compar:IA</a>
        — to estimate the energy balance of generative-AI model inference. This lets you compare the environmental
        impact of different models for the same request. Transparency is essential to encourage the development and
        adoption of more eco-responsible AI models.
      </p>

      <p>
        Ecologits applies life-cycle assessment (LCA) principles following the <strong class="text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">ISO 14044</strong>
        standard, focusing for now on the impact of <em>inference</em> (using models to answer requests) and the
        manufacturing of graphics cards (resource extraction, manufacturing, and transport).
      </p>

      <p>
        The model's electricity consumption is estimated from parameters such as the size and architecture of the
        model, the location of the servers where the models are deployed, and the number of output tokens. The
        climate-change potential indicator, expressed in <strong class="text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300">CO₂-equivalent</strong>,
        is derived from the electricity-consumption measurement.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-500 italic">
        Methodologies for assessing the environmental impact of AI are still under development.
      </p>

      <div class="rounded-lg bg-neutral-50 dark:bg-neutral-900/40 border n-main-border p-3 text-xs text-neutral-500 dark:text-neutral-400">
        <p class="font-medium text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-300 mb-1">Data source</p>
        <p>
          Per-model consumption (mWh per 1000 tokens) from the
          <a href="https://comparia.beta.gouv.fr/ranking" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 underline">Comparia model-energy dataset</a>
          — <span class="font-medium">licence Etalab 2.0</span>, snapshot dated <span class="font-medium">2 July 2026</span>.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-1.5">
          Models absent from the dataset (notably most API-only models, whose consumption is reported as <code class="px-1 py-0.5 rounded bg-neutral-100 dark:bg-neutral-900 text-pink-600 dark:text-pink-400 font-mono">N/A</code>)
          use a fallback coefficient — marked with <span class="font-medium">*</span> in the breakdowns above.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </details>
</section>